issue_title: Split sanity.openjdk into parallel jobs
creator: pshipton
text:
Bug Title: Split sanity.openjdk into parallel jobs
Bug Description: Recently security1, 2, 4 were added to sanity.openjdk, taking more time to run the testing. Also some of the OpenJ9 machines are slow and take longer to get through all the testing. I'm also told that security3 will be added to sanity so that all OpenJDK tier1 and tier2 tests are part of sanity. I believe security3 takes ~1 hour for a single variant.
I suggest we split sanity.openjdk into 3 parallel jobs to start, and see how that goes.
@llxia

issue_title: Recent JDK build failures
description:
An example can be seen in Creating java.base.jmod
 Compiling up to 3 files for BUILD_DEMO_CodePointIM
 Updating support/demos/image/jfc/CodePointIM/src.zip
 openjdk version "22-internal" 2024-03-19
 OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 22-internal-adhoc.jenkins.buildjdknextx86-64windowsopenjdk)
 Eclipse OpenJ9 VM (build master-548af364c14, JRE 22 Windows Server 2019 amd64-64-Bit Compressed References 20230707_461 (JIT enabled, AOT enabled)
 OpenJ9 - 548af364c14
 OMR - bcc94e42952
 JCL - a9561f1964e based on jdk-22+5)
 Compiling up to 3 files for BUILD_DEMO_FileChooserDemo
 Updating support/demos/image/jfc/FileChooserDemo/src.zip
 Error: Resolution failed: Module java.compiler not found, required by jdk.jdeps
 make[3]: [CreateJmods.gmk:245: /cygdrive/f/users/jenkins/workspace/build_jdknext_x86-64_windows_openjdk/build/windows-x86_64-server-release/support/images/jmods/_create_java.base.jmod_exec.marker] Error 2
 make[2]: [make/Main.gmk:420: java.base-jmod] Error 2
 make[2]: Waiting for unfinished jobs....
 Creating java.compiler.jmod
I was able to reproduce the problem on Linux using `make JOBS=1 jdk.jdeps-jmod` then `make JOBS=1 java.base-jmod`.
I suspect a dependency is missing, leaving it to chance whether `java.compiler` is available in time or not. `closed/custom/Main.gmk` defines `DEFAULT_JMOD_DEPS` which was used prior to
* [8217739: Cannot reuse java.base UnixConstants.java from target in BuildJDK when cross compiling](
but has no benefit now in jdk17+.

issue_title: Make j9javaaccessflags.h more readable
description: The constants in [j9javaaccessflags.h]( are not organized in a way where it is obvious which bits are available for new entries. The suggestion in this issue is to reorganize these in a more manageable way.
creator: theresa-m
text:
Bug Title: Make j9javaaccessflags.h more readable
Bug Description: The constants in [j9javaaccessflags.h]( are not organized in a way where it is obvious which bits are available for new entries. The suggestion in this issue is to reorganize these in a more manageable way.

Summary of problem
JDK 17.0.7 crashed when the test programe is executed, but JDK 11.0.19 and JDK8u372 didn't.
Reproduce steps
1. Copy the source code `Case.java`
import java.lang.ref.PhantomReference;
public class Case {
 private static PhantomReference<Object> reference;
 public static void main(String[] var0) throws Exception {
 sumReductionInit(new long[262144], new long[262144], new long[262144]);
 }
 public static void sumReductionInit(long[] l1, long[] l2, long[] l3) {
 reference.get();
 }
}
2. compile and run the program with JDK 17.0.7 & JDK 11.0.19 & JDK8u372 > jdk-17.0.7+7_openj9\bin\java Case
Exception in thread "main" <hex> omrport.359 * ** ASSERTION FAILED ** at c:\workspace\openjdk-build\workspace\build\src\omr\port\common\omrmemtag.c:145: ((memoryCorruptionDetected))

issue_title: Investigate behaviour of Thread.stop() on suspended threads
description: In #17806 we changed the behaviour of JVMTI `StopThread()` to no longer resume a suspended thread. We need to see if a similar change should be made to the java `Thread.stop()` which is implemented seperately.
creator: gacholio

issue_title: jlink is not reproducible
description:
I've been trying to get jlink from openj9 to make bit-for-bit reproducible jlink images, however there seems to be an issue specific to openj9 that is causing the resultant images to be non-reproducible. This is easily noticeable with a test-case:
wget tar -xf ibm-semeru-open-jdk_x64_linux_17.0.7_7_openj9-0.38.0.tar.gz
mv jdk-17.0.7+7/ semeru-17
# Create some sample images:
semeru-17/bin/jlink --add-modules java.base,java.compiler --output semeru1
semeru-17/bin/jlink --add-modules java.base,java.compiler --output semeru2
# Normalize modify timestamps
find semeru* -exec touch --date=0 --no-dereference {} \;
# Run diffoscope ( to show differences:
docker run --rm -t -w $(pwd) -v $(pwd):$(pwd):ro \
 registry.salsa.debian.org/reproducible-builds/diffoscope semeru1 semeru2
This returns with an output like the following:
 semeru1
 semeru2
│ semeru1/lib
├── semeru2/lib
│ │ semeru1/lib/modules
│ ├── semeru2/lib/modules
│ │ @@ -24033,15 +24033,15 @@
│ │ 0005de00: 7479 7065 0802 b501 0015 6a61 7661 782e type......javax.
│ │ 0005de10: 6c61 6e67 2e6d 6f64 656c 2e75 7469 6c08 lang.model.util.
│ │ 0005de20: 02b7 0100 0b6a 6176 6178 2e74 6f6f 6c73 .....javax.tools
│ │ 0005de30: 0802 b901 001d 6a61 7661 782e 746f 6f6c ......javax.tool
│ │ 0005de40: 732e 446f 6375 6d65 6e74 6174 696f 6e54 s.DocumentationT
│ │ 0005de50: 6f6f 6c08 02bb 0100 186a 6176 6178 2e74 ool......javax.t
│ │ 0005de60: 6f6f 6c73 2e4a 6176 6143 6f6d 7069 6c65 ools.JavaCompile
│ │ +0005de70: 7208 02bd 0300 bb67 a201 000d 6d6f 6475 r......g....modu
│ │ -0005de70: 7208 02bd 0344 09b1 fb01 000d 6d6f 6475 r....D......modu
│ │ 0005de80: 6c65 5461 7267 6574 7301 0025 2829 5b4c leTargets..%()[L
│ │ 0005de90: 6a64 6b2f 696e 7465 726e 616c 2f6d 6f64 jdk/internal/mod
│ │ 0005dea0: 756c 652f 4d6f 6475 6c65 5461 7267 6574 ule/ModuleTarget
│ │ 0005deb0: 3b01 0020 6a64 6b2f 696e 7465 726e 616c ;.. jdk/internal
│ │ 0005dec0: 2f6d 6f64 756c 652f 4d6f 6475 6c65 5461 /module/ModuleTa
│ │ 0005ded0: 7267 6574 0702 c201 000b 6c69 6e75 782d rget......linux-
│ │ 0005dee0: 616d 6436 3408 02c4 0a02 c300 1701 000c amd64...........
Note that if more modules are used the result will be more binary differences in lib/modules. Hotspot-based JDKs don't exhibit this behavior:
wget tar -xf OpenJDK17U-jdk_x64_linux_hotspot_17.0.7_7.tar.gz
mv jdk-17.0.7+7/ temurin-17
# Create some sample images:
temurin-17/bin/jlink --add-modules java.base,java.compiler --output temurin1
temurin-17/bin/jlink --add-modules java.base,java.compiler --output temurin2
# Normalize modify timestamps
find temurin* -exec touch --date=0 --no-dereference {} \;
# Run diffoscope ( to show differences:
docker run --rm -t -w $(pwd) -v $(pwd):$(pwd):ro \
 registry.salsa.debian.org/reproducible-builds/diffoscope temurin1 temurin2
There will be no output which indicates that the two images are identical. It would be great if this could be resolved so that we can update our build pipelines to be reproducible.
creator: ReillyBrogan

issue_title: triggerOneOffDump() should take const char* parameters
description:
There are a few `triggerOneOffDump()` usages with string constants:
If this code snippet is applied in a C++ file, compilation failed with error: ISO C++ forbids converting a string constant to 'char*' [-Werror=write-strings]
Refactoring `triggerOneOffDump()` parameters require changes in a few other methods including OMR helpers:
 OMR helper and its callers
creator: JasonFengJ9
text:
Bug Title: triggerOneOffDump() should take const char* parameters
Bug Description: There are a few `triggerOneOffDump()` usages with string constants:
If this code snippet is applied in a C++ file, compilation failed with error: ISO C++ forbids converting a string constant to 'char*' [-Werror=write-strings]
Refactoring `triggerOneOffDump()` parameters require changes in a few other methods including OMR helpers:
 OMR helper and its callers

issue_title: JEP 454: Foreign Function & Memory API (Finalized)
description:
See with the following changes in terms of APIs which might affect our FFI implementation in Java after the updated code at (Third Preview).
1.Provided a new linker option allowing clients to pass heap segments to downcall method handles
2.Introduced the `Enable-Native-Access` JAR-file manifest attribute, allowing code in executable JAR files to call restricted methods without having to use the --enable-native-access command-line option
3.Enabled clients to build C-language function descriptors programmatically, avoiding platform-specific constants
4.Improved support for variable-length arrays in native memory
5.Added support for arbitrary charsets for native strings
FYI: @tajila, @pshipton
creator: ChengJin01
text:
Bug Title: JEP 454: Foreign Function & Memory API (Finalized)
Bug Description: See with the following changes in terms of APIs which might affect our FFI implementation in Java after the updated code at (Third Preview).
1.Provided a new linker option allowing clients to pass heap segments to downcall method handles
2.Introduced the `Enable-Native-Access` JAR-file manifest attribute, allowing code in executable JAR files to call restricted methods without having to use the --enable-native-access command-line option
3.Enabled clients to build C-language function descriptors programmatically, avoiding platform-specific constants
4.Improved support for variable-length arrays in native memory
5.Added support for arbitrary charsets for native strings
FYI: @tajila, @pshipton

issue_title: Value Types: GC crash in VM_ValueTypeHelpers::loadFlattenableArrayElement when array flattening is enabled
description:
I'm seeing a GC [1] crash after the `System.arraycopy` (not JIT'd) is invoked from a JIT'd method (`TestSystemArrayCopy.test`). Here is the test I used: [testsrc.zip]( The source array is flattened. The destination array is not [2].
`java -Xnocompressedrefs -Xshareclasses:none -Xverify:none -XX:+EnableValhalla -XX:+EnableArrayFlattening -XX:ValueTypeFlatteningThreshold=999999 '-Xjit:limit={*TestSystemArrayCopy.test*},count=1,disableAsyncCompilation,disableArrayCopyOpts' TestSystemArrayCopy` The test runs with enabling the array flattening and `disableArrayCopyOpts` that makes sure there is no `System.arraycopy` transformation in the JIT. The GC crash happens in `VM_ValueTypeHelpers::loadFlattenableArrayElement.` The sequence of events is as below:
TestSystemArrayCopy.test (JIT'd, the only JIT'd method in this test: limit={*TestSystemArrayCopy.test*})

 pushObjectInSpecialFrame srcObject
 pushObjectInSpecialFrame destObject

issue_title: [FFI] Mixed code in the JDK21 extension repo on Power
description:
I notice that are currently merged with the Hostpot specific code intended for `pLinux` as follows:
/linux
ABIv2CallArranger.java
CallArranger.java
PPC64Architecture.java
TypeClass.java
which is wrong as these code are specific to the Hotspot implementation which doesn't belong the `openj9` branch.
If we keep them there, it is easy to mess things up in compilation with such confusion.
FYI: @tajila, @pshipton
creator: ChengJin01
text:

issue_title: Checklist for Java new level bringup
description:
* Add preprocessor configuration for Java new level
* Add `jvmtitests excludes XML` file for Java new level * Add `TestConfig latest exclude` file for Java new level
* Add `openjdk/excludes/ProblemList_openjdk-openj9` file for Java new level
* Optionally remove the out-of-service configurations
The Next Java new level is Java 23.

issue_title: Override TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isCompilable() for JITServer
description:
`TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isCompilable()` accesses some fields from JavaVM and it's not safe to use as is in out-of-process compilations.
To fix this we have two alternatives:
1. When the server constructs a ResolvedJ9Method, a mirror resolved method is also built at the client. When that happens we can precompute the `isCompilable` information and store it into a boolean field which will be passed to the server. The disadvantage is that we have to precompute this field even though the optimizer may not ask about it.
2. For each client, store at the server the JavaVM fields that `isCompilable` is asking for.
Solution 2 should be preferred because it has less overhead. However, solution 2 is contingent on these JavaVM fields being populated exactly once before first compilation takes place:
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextMethodID1
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextMethodID2
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextPermissionMethodID1
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextPermissionMethodID2
javaVM->nativeLibrariesLoadMethodID
creator: mpirvu
text:
Bug Title: Override TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isCompilable() for JITServer
Bug Description: `TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isCompilable()` accesses some fields from JavaVM and it's not safe to use as is in out-of-process compilations.
To fix this we have two alternatives:
1. When the server constructs a ResolvedJ9Method, a mirror resolved method is also built at the client. When that happens we can precompute the `isCompilable` information and store it into a boolean field which will be passed to the server. The disadvantage is that we have to precompute this field even though the optimizer may not ask about it.
2. For each client, store at the server the JavaVM fields that `isCompilable` is asking for.
Solution 2 should be preferred because it has less overhead. However, solution 2 is contingent on these JavaVM fields being populated exactly once before first compilation takes place:
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextMethodID1
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextMethodID2
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextPermissionMethodID1
javaVM->doPrivilegedWithContextPermissionMethodID2
javaVM->nativeLibrariesLoadMethodID

issue_title: Add tests to verify JITServer with SSL enabled
description:
Add tests to the existing `criu` tests under `cmdLineTests` for checking/verifying SSL connections.
Currently we do not have tests to verify JITServer with SSL enabled, so another test under `jitserver` in `cmdLineTests` needs to be added too.

text:

Currently we do not have tests to verify JITServer with SSL enabled, so another test under `jitserver` in `cmdLineTests` needs to be added too.

issue_title: java.exe Crashes when JPackage Bundles it
description:
I've been happily deploying & running my application with OpenJ9 17.0.6+10. I deploy my app with JPackage.
I tried to bump up the used JDK to 20.0.2+9 (and 19.0.2+7).
As soon as I run `java.exe` in the deployed application (JPackage bundles the JDK/JRE alongside the app), the whole JVM crashes.
I mean simply run `java.exe ` I don't even need to pass any arguments to it.
This happens on Windows 11.
Here's what's printed into the console:

Bug Title: java.exe Crashes when JPackage Bundles it
Bug Description: I've been happily deploying & running my application with OpenJ9 17.0.6+10. I deploy my app with JPackage.
I tried to bump up the used JDK to 20.0.2+9 (and 19.0.2+7).

creator: pshipton

issue_title: OpenJDK test flag vm.continuations is false but should be true
description:
If there are tests that fail when vm.continuations is set to true, we should exclude them and create issues to track.
@babsingh fyi
creator: pshipton

issue_title: OpenJDK test flag vm.opt.final.ClassUnloading should be true
description: It seems vm.opt.final.ClassUnloading should be true. It was set to false by due to a particular Hotspot centric test. However the flag should be true and the test should be excluded.
creator: pshipton
text:
Bug Title: OpenJDK test flag vm.opt.final.ClassUnloading should be true
Bug Description: It seems vm.opt.final.ClassUnloading should be true. It was set to false by due to a particular Hotspot centric test. However the flag should be true and the test should be excluded.

issue_title: RedefinePreviousVersions not supported by OpenJ9
description:
`serviceability/jvmti/RedefineClasses/RedefinePreviousVersions.java` tests Hotspot specific cmd line options which
are not supported in OpenJ9:
-Xlog:redefine+class+iklass+add=trace,redefine+class+iklass+purge=trace
Test source code: Setting `vm.opt.final.ClassUnloading` to true enables this test.
This test will be permanently disabled for OpenJ9 since the above options are not supported by OpenJ9.
creator: babsingh
text:

This test will be permanently disabled for OpenJ9 since the above options are not supported by OpenJ9.

issue_title: CRIUSupport: Add multi-threaded hooks
description:
enum HookMode {
 SINGLE_THREAD,
 MULTI_THREAD
 }
 /**
 * User hook that is run before checkpointing the JVM.
 *
 * If single-threaded mode is requested, no other application threads
 * will be active. Users should avoid synchronization of objects that are not owned
 * by the thread, terminally blocking operations and launching new threads in the hook.
 * If the thread attempts to acquire a lock that it doesn't own, an exception will
 * be thrown.
 *
 * If multi-threaded mode is requested, the hook will be run alongside all other active Java threads.
 * * High priority hooks are run last before checkpoint, and vice-versa for low priority hooks.
 * The priority of the hook is with respect to the other hooks run within that mode. Multi-threaded
 * hooks are implicitly lower priority than single-threaded hooks. Ie. the lowest priority single-threaded
 * hook is higher priority than the highest priority multi-threaded hook. * * @param hook user hook
 * @param hookMode mode in which the hook is run, either multi-threaded or single-threaded
 * @param priority the priority of the hook, between 0 - 99. Throws UnsupportedOperationException otherwise.
 * @return this
 */
 public CRIUSupport registerPreCheckpointHook(Runnable hook, HookMode mode, int priority) throws UnsupportedOperationException
 /**
 * User hook that is run after restoring a checkpoint image.
 *
 * If single-threaded mode is requested, no other application threads
 * will be active. Users should avoid synchronization of objects that are not owned
 * by the thread, terminally blocking operations and launching new threads in the hook.
 * If the thread attempts to acquire a lock that it doesn't own, an exception will
 * be thrown.
 *
 * If multi-threaded mode is requested, the hook will be run alongside all other active Java threads.
 * * High priority hooks are run first after restore, and vice-versa for low priority hooks.
 * The priority of the hook is with respect to the other hooks run within that mode. Multi-threaded
 * hooks are implicitly lower priority than single-threaded hooks. Ie. the lowest priority single-threaded
 * hook is higher priority than the highest priority multi-threaded hook. * * @param hook user hook
 * @param hookMode mode in which the hook is run, either multi-threaded or single-threaded
 * @param priority the priority of the hook, between 0 - 99. Throws UnsupportedOperationException otherwise.
 * @return this
 */
 public CRIUSupport registerPostRestoreHook(Runnable hook, HookMode mode, int priority) throws UnsupportedOperationException

issue_title: Crash in prepareToFixMemberNames()
description:
Last week a curious crash appeared in a PR build: I think the crash data is no longer available for download, but I have a copy. The crash is unrelated to the PR - analysis follows.
Crashing frame:
frame #14: <hex> libj9vm29.dylib`::getJNIMethodID(J9VMThread *, J9Method *) [inlined] ensureJNIIDTable(currentThread=<hex>, clazz=<hex>) at jnicsup.cpp:2156:26 [opt]
J9ClassLoader * classLoader = clazz->classLoader;
...
if (classLoader->jniIDs == NULL) { < crash here with null classLoader
It looks like this `clazz` has been unloaded:
> !j9class <hex>
J9Class at <hex> {
 Fields for J9Class:
 <hex>: UDATA classDepthAndFlags = <hex> (135135233) < J9AccClassDying is set
 ...
 <hex>: struct J9ClassLoader* classLoader = !j9classloader <hex> < null
 <hex>: struct J9Object* classObject = !j9object <hex><FAULT> < J9_INVALID_OBJECT
 ...
}
Class name: java/lang/invoke/LambdaForm$DMH/<hex>
We're trying to get the JNI method ID for `J9Method` <hex>:
frame #15: <hex> libj9vm29.dylib`::getJNIMethodID(currentThread=<hex>, method=<hex>) at jnicsup.cpp:2281:11 [opt]
which is (or I guess was):
java/lang/invoke/LambdaForm$DMH/<hex>.invokeVirtual(Ljava/lang/Object;Ljava/lang/Object;JI)J
This is happening as part of `prepareToFixMemberNames()`, which has come across what looks to be a `MemberName` that could be affected by class redefinition.
frame #16: <hex> libj9jvmti29.dylib`prepareToFixMemberNamesObjectIteratorCallback(vm=<hex>, objectDesc=<unavailable>, userData=<hex>) at hshelp.c:1757:33 [opt]
UDATA vmtarget = (UDATA)J9OBJECT_U64_LOAD(currentThread, object, vm->vmtargetOffset);
...
J9JNIMethodID *methodID = currentThread->javaVM->internalVMFunctions->getJNIMethodID(currentThread, (J9Method *)vmtarget); < crash here
(lldb) p object
(j9object_t) $6 = <hex>
> !j9object <hex>
!J9Object <hex> {
 struct J9Class* clazz = !j9class <hex> // java/lang/invoke/MemberName
 Object flags = <hex>;
 I lockword = <hex> (offset = 0) (java/lang/Object) <hidden>
 Ljava/lang/Class; clazz = !fj9object <hex> (offset = 20) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 Ljava/lang/String; name = !fj9object <hex> (offset = 24) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 Ljava/lang/Object; type = !fj9object <hex> (offset = 28) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 I flags = <hex> (offset = 40) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 Ljava/lang/invoke/ResolvedMethodName; method = !fj9object <hex> (offset = 32) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 Ljava/lang/Object; resolution = !fj9object <hex> (offset = 36) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName)
 J vmindex = <hex> (offset = 12) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName) <hidden>
 J vmtarget = <hex> (offset = 4) (java/lang/invoke/MemberName) <hidden>
}
This `clazz` is the `java/lang/Class` of `org/openj9/test/invoker/Dummy` (<hex>), which is unrelated to the (unloaded) `clazz` above. Additionally, the `type` is a `MethodType` that does not correspond to the signature of the `vmtarget`, and `name` is a bogus reference. It also doesn't show up when listing `MemberName` instances in MAT. So I think this object is dead but not yet overwritten.
Is `j9mm_iterate_all_objects()` supposed to be able to report dead objects? (Without `j9mm_iterator_flag_include_holes`, I mean.) I see that it makes an effort to skip objects whose classes are flagged with `J9AccClassDying`, but that doesn't help in this case. It would be very tricky - maybe even impossible - to ensure that dead objects are reliably handled in `prepareToFixMemberNames()`.

issue_title: CRIU: Add api to query restore time
description:
In internal CRIUSupport
 /**
 * Retrieve the time when the last restore occurred. In the case of multiple restores
 * the previous times are overwritten
 *
 * @return the time in milliseconds. -ve value if restore has not occured.
 */
 public static long getLastRestoreTime();
creator: tajila
text:
Bug Title: CRIU: Add api to query restore time
Bug Description: In internal CRIUSupport
 /**
 * Retrieve the time when the last restore occurred. In the case of multiple restores
 * the previous times are overwritten
 *
 * @return the time in milliseconds. -ve value if restore has not occured.
 */
 public static long getLastRestoreTime();

issue_title: Remove --with-mixedrefs configuration option
description: All versions on all platforms have for some time been using mixed references; we no longer need the `--with-mixedrefs` configuration option (and its associated complexity).
creator: keithc-ca
text:
Bug Title: Remove --with-mixedrefs configuration option
Bug Description: All versions on all platforms have for some time been using mixed references; we no longer need the `--with-mixedrefs` configuration option (and its associated complexity).

issue_title: Some JVMTI tests in cmdLineTester_jvmtitests_hcr hang with -XX:+DynamicHeapification
description:
Some JVMTI tests in cmdLineTester_jvmtitests_hcr are hanging when run with `-XX:+DynamicHeapification`, even with Escape Analysis disabled. I have links to internal grinder runs using a recent nightly build, one with options `-XX:+DynamicHeapification -XX:+MergeCompilerOptions -Xjit:disableEscapeAnalysis`[1] and a second with options `-XX:-DynamicHeapification -XX:+MergeCompilerOptions -Xjit:disableEscapeAnalysis`.[2].
I tried to track down when the problem first came up, and it looks like it might have been OpenJ9 commit 9a795f12185eaa1f7dd0f21e7d19d52249108b07 and OMR commit [34b6ba4]( - I can reproduce the problem using a build after that point, but not before. (Before that point, I see two failures with Metronome GC policy, but I think they're not quite as important as these hangs.)
[1] [2] _Originally posted by @hzongaro in

issue_title: Implement StackWalker.Option.DROP_METHOD_INFO
description:

There are also tests that expect that the related features of `StackFrame` will throw `UnsupportedOperationException`.
See also #18100.

issue_title: Remove Q type checks in Valhalla code
description:
Currently many places in the VM rely on Q type check for the null-restricted value type. The Q type is going to be removed in the future. L type will be used for all value types, no matter it is null-restricted or not. For the fields, the Q type is going to be replaced with null-restricted attribute,
Also the keyword "primitive" is going to be removed.
The null restricted fields will be treated the same as Q type fields. For now, we need to add null-restricted attribute checks into the places where we are doing Q type field checks. After javac is updated, we can remove the Q type checks completely.
Some of our testing code is generating Q types and using "primitive", they need to be updated as well.
creator: hangshao0
text:
Bug Title: Remove Q type checks in Valhalla code 
Bug Description: Currently many places in the VM rely on Q type check for the null-restricted value type. The Q type is going to be removed in the future. L type will be used for all value types, no matter it is null-restricted or not. For the fields, the Q type is going to be replaced with null-restricted attribute,
Also the keyword "primitive" is going to be removed.
The null restricted fields will be treated the same as Q type fields. For now, we need to add null-restricted attribute checks into the places where we are doing Q type field checks. After javac is updated, we can remove the Q type checks completely.
Some of our testing code is generating Q types and using "primitive", they need to be updated as well.

issue_title: Value Types: Replace checking Q type with checking NullRestricted attribute
description:
As mentioned in `NullRestricted` attribute is introduced. This issue is created to track all changes required in the JIT to replace checking Q type with checking `NullRestricted` attribute. Below is a list of files that currently checks/use Q type. - [x] 1-7 and 9-11: Being updated in #18179
- [x] 8: ~Not sure how to deal with it at the moment~
 - - - [ ] 12: Simple change of removal once Q type is completely gone
1. addEntryForFieldImpl
2. TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isFieldQType
3. TR_ResolvedJ9JITServerMethod::isFieldQType
4. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::loadInstance
5. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::genWithField
6. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::storeInstance
7. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::storeStatic
8. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::genAconst_init
9. J9::ClassEnv::isClassRefPrimitiveValueType
10. JITClientCompilationThread.cpp
11. MessageTypes.hpp and MessageTypes.cpp
12. A list of files that we can simply remove using `Q` type from when `Q` is no longer generated in the signature
creator: a7ehuo
text:

This issue is created to track all changes required in the JIT to replace checking Q type with checking `NullRestricted` attribute. Below is a list of files that currently checks/use Q type. - [x] 1-7 and 9-11: Being updated in #18179
- [x] 8: ~Not sure how to deal with it at the moment~
 - - - [ ] 12: Simple change of removal once Q type is completely gone
1. addEntryForFieldImpl
2. TR_ResolvedJ9Method::isFieldQType
3. TR_ResolvedJ9JITServerMethod::isFieldQType
4. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::loadInstance
5. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::genWithField
6. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::storeInstance
7. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::storeStatic
8. TR_J9ByteCodeIlGenerator::genAconst_init
9. J9::ClassEnv::isClassRefPrimitiveValueType
10. JITClientCompilationThread.cpp
11. MessageTypes.hpp and MessageTypes.cpp
12. A list of files that we can simply remove using `Q` type from when `Q` is no longer generated in the signature

issue_title: Use a shorter name for OPENJ9_ENABLE_OPENJDK_CRAC_SUPPORT
description:
I suggest `OPENJ9_ENABLE_CRAC_SUPPORT` which would be more consistent with `OPENJ9_ENABLE_CRIU_SUPPORT`.
I don't think "OPENJDK" is an appropriate part of the name. We could also remove that segment of the UMA flag.
If we want to change the name, it will be better to do it sooner rather than later.
@JasonFengJ9 @tajila
creator: keithc-ca

issue_title: Remove jextract in jdk21
description: The OpenJ9 jextract executable has been duplicated by jpackcore, and the OpenJ9 jextract is deprecated. Remove the OpenJ9 jextract executable in the jdk21 GA release in order to force users to use jpackcore. In some later release OpenJDK will introduce a jextract tool for a different purpose, and it may reduce confusion to have the OpenJ9 tool gone earlier.
creator: pshipton
text:
Bug Title: Remove jextract in jdk21
Bug Description: The OpenJ9 jextract executable has been duplicated by jpackcore, and the OpenJ9 jextract is deprecated. Remove the OpenJ9 jextract executable in the jdk21 GA release in order to force users to use jpackcore. In some later release OpenJDK will introduce a jextract tool for a different purpose, and it may reduce confusion to have the OpenJ9 tool gone earlier.

issue_title: Possible missing dependency in the auto generated header files
description:
While investigating [illegal instruction issue-16468]( I found something odd related to the auto generated header files in the build process on X86.
The [jitConfig]( offset (`J9TR_JavaVMJitConfig`) in `J9JavaVM` can change build by build. I believe it’s most of the time due to [jclConstantPool]( field.
c++
 struct J9RAMConstantPoolItem jclConstantPool[J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE];
 ...
 struct J9JITConfig* jitConfig;
The size of `jclConstantPool[J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE]` changes if `J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE` changes, which will affect the offset for `jitConfig`. I believe `J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE` is calculated based on [vmconstantpool.xml]( and it is auto generated in `j9vmconstantpool.h` during the build process. The offset `J9TR_JavaVMJitConfig` is also generated in `jilconsts.inc` during the build process. The chain of dependency we are looking at is vmconstantpool.xml => J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE (j9vmconstantpool.h) => J9TR_JavaVMJitConfig (jilconsts.inc) => X86Unresolveds.nasm.o
If [vmconstantpool.xml]( has been updated, I found
1. Doing an incremental build (“make images” or “make all”) will not rebuild `jilconsts.inc` after `J9VM_VMCONSTANTPOOL_SIZE` is updated in `j9vmconstantpool.h`
2. Just remove both `jilconsts.inc` and `jilvalues.m4` under `build/linux-x86_64-server-release/vm/runtime/oti` and do an incremental build: `jilconsts.inc` and `jilvalues.m4` will be rebuilt with the correct offset, however `X86Unresolveds.nasm.o` will not be rebuilt and still contains the wrong offset
3. Remove the whole `build` directory: The correct offset will finally get updated in `X86Unresolveds.nasm.o` in the clean rebuild.
Looks like I'm force to do a clean build every time if I don’t want to check if [vmconstantpool.xml]( has been updated or not

issue_title: Openj9 compatibility options
description:
`-XX:Compatibility=[compatibilityMode]`
This option allows the JDK to run in compatibility mode to support applications that require specific capabilities.
Some examples are cases where applications rely on vendor-specific command line arguments to be processed, or cases where unspecified APIs are to be made available.
We will determine which applications we will provide compatibility mode for. If an unsupported mode is specified, we will fail to start the JVM.
Initially, we will only support a single usage of this option. That is `-XX:Compatibility=mode1` ` -XX:Compatibility=mode2` will not be supported.
We reserve the right to remove or modify the behaviour of these options at any time.
The first usage of this option will be `-XX:Compatibility=elasticsearch`. Mode names will not be case-sensitive, so one could equivalently say `-XX:Compatibility=ElasticSearch`. With the `elasticsearch` compatibility mode, OpenJ9 may accept or appear to support Hotspot-specific options or APIs in ways that enhance compatibility to run elasticsearch workloads. More modes may be added in the future.
creator: tajila
text:
Bug Title: Openj9 compatibility options
Bug Description: `-XX:Compatibility=[compatibilityMode]`
This option allows the JDK to run in compatibility mode to support applications that require specific capabilities.
Some examples are cases where applications rely on vendor-specific command line arguments to be processed, or cases where unspecified APIs are to be made available.
We will determine which applications we will provide compatibility mode for. If an unsupported mode is specified, we will fail to start the JVM.
Initially, we will only support a single usage of this option. That is `-XX:Compatibility=mode1` ` -XX:Compatibility=mode2` will not be supported.
We reserve the right to remove or modify the behaviour of these options at any time.
The first usage of this option will be `-XX:Compatibility=elasticsearch`. Mode names will not be case-sensitive, so one could equivalently say `-XX:Compatibility=ElasticSearch`. With the `elasticsearch` compatibility mode, OpenJ9 may accept or appear to support Hotspot-specific options or APIs in ways that enhance compatibility to run elasticsearch workloads. More modes may be added in the future.

issue_title: CRIU: Support for clearing sensitive data at checkpoint
description:
When a checkpoint is taken the entire contents of the process is serialized. It is possible that someone can inspect the serialized state to capture some sensitive information about the application. 1) Zero freed memory
One way to address this is to make sure that all sensitive data is cleared by the application. However, the best an application can do is to clear references to sensitive data, only the GC can ensure that the sensitive data is cleared. To provide better security gaurantess I propose the following:
In the `J9MMCONSTANT_EXPLICIT_GC_PREPARE_FOR_CHECKPOINT` GC we can additional make sure all zeroed memory is cleared. Since this is GC runs after the checkpoint hooks we can provide a guarantee that if sensitive data is no longer referenced it will be removed from the serialized output at checkpoint.
2) Automatic obfuscation
A more advance approach is to provide an annotation `@sensitive` which can be applied to any field. This annotation indicates to the JVM that the field should be encrypted and checkpoint time and decrypted upon restore. //Current we are not concerned with 2), just leaving it here so we can continue to think about it.
creator: tajila
text:
Bug Title: CRIU: Support for clearing sensitive data at checkpoint
Bug Description: When a checkpoint is taken the entire contents of the process is serialized. It is possible that someone can inspect the serialized state to capture some sensitive information about the application. 1) Zero freed memory
One way to address this is to make sure that all sensitive data is cleared by the application. However, the best an application can do is to clear references to sensitive data, only the GC can ensure that the sensitive data is cleared. To provide better security gaurantess I propose the following:
In the `J9MMCONSTANT_EXPLICIT_GC_PREPARE_FOR_CHECKPOINT` GC we can additional make sure all zeroed memory is cleared. Since this is GC runs after the checkpoint hooks we can provide a guarantee that if sensitive data is no longer referenced it will be removed from the serialized output at checkpoint.
2) Automatic obfuscation
A more advance approach is to provide an annotation `@sensitive` which can be applied to any field. This annotation indicates to the JVM that the field should be encrypted and checkpoint time and decrypted upon restore. //Current we are not concerned with 2), just leaving it here so we can continue to think about it.

issue_title: Remove bytecodes aconst_init, withfield and <vnew> method from Valhalla
description:
The new bytecodes `aconst_init` and `withfield` previously introduced in Project Valhalla is going to be removed. Value Type initialization will be done via existing bytecodes `new`, `dup` and `putfield`.
The special Value Type constructor `<vnew>` is also going to be removed. It will be replaced with regulated constructor (mentioned in #18309).
creator: hangshao0
text:
Bug Title: Remove bytecodes aconst_init, withfield and <vnew> method from Valhalla
Bug Description: The new bytecodes `aconst_init` and `withfield` previously introduced in Project Valhalla is going to be removed. Value Type initialization will be done via existing bytecodes `new`, `dup` and `putfield`.
The special Value Type constructor `<vnew>` is also going to be removed. It will be replaced with regulated constructor (mentioned in #18309).

issue_title: JDK22+ disable Java22andUp JEP 454 tests
description:
[Java22andUp JEP 454 tests]( requires [the OpenJDK updates]( which is still in `openj9-staging` branch. [Valhalla extension repo]( doesn't have such updates either.
PR builds against these JEP 454 tests failed at jep454/downcall/InvalidDownCallTests.java:35: error: Arena is a preview API and is disabled by default.
 [javac] import java.lang.foreign.Arena;
 [javac] ^
 [javac] (use --enable-preview to enable preview APIs)
or
 [javac] /home/jenkins/workspace/Grinder/aqa-tests/functional/Java22andUp/src/org/openj9/test/jep454/upcall/UpcallMHWithPrimTests.java:689: error: cannot find symbol
 [javac] MemorySegment doubleSegmt = arena.allocateFrom(JAVA_DOUBLE, 1159.748D);
 [javac] ^
 [javac] symbol: method allocateFrom(OfDouble,double)
 [javac] location: variable arena of type Arena
FYI @ChengJin01 Disabling JEP 454 tests until Valhalla extension repo has the OpenJDK API updates.
creator: JasonFengJ9

issue_title: Virtual Thread Support for JVMTI Extensions API
description:
We need to mirror changes for virtual thread support to the JVMTI Extensions API.
Currently, the following functions need virtual thread support:
We should also double check other JVMTI Extensions API for missing virtual thread support.
The JVMTI Extensions API is not regulated by specification. So, it shouldn't block any release. But, it might affect consumers of the JVMTI Extensions API.

issue_title: jdk8,11 Ignore  "allow" and "disallow" set via the java.security.manager system property
description:
Copied from Oracle 8/11.0.21 release notes.
[➜]( Ignore Allow and Disallow Options for java.security.manager System Property ([JDK-8301118](
In JDK 12, two new token options for the java.security.manager system property, "allow" and "disallow", were introduced.
Many applications and frameworks are designed to run on multiple JDKs. For those that enable the SecurityManager at runtime via System.setSecurityManager, they have to specify the "allow" option as of JDK 18 (see [JDK-8203316]( However, these applications would also prefer to use the same command line across multiple versions of the JDK, especially if it is not known what JDK version a user will use.
Currently, if these options are specified in JDK 12 or earlier, the runtime attempts to load a SecurityManager implementation with the classname "allow" or "disallow", which results in a Could not create SecurityManager Error and the application will not start up.
From this release onward, the "allow" and "disallow" options for the java.security.manager system property will be ignored.
creator: pshipton
text:
Bug Title: jdk8,11 Ignore  "allow" and "disallow" set via the java.security.manager system property
Bug Description: Copied from Oracle 8/11.0.21 release notes.
[➜]( Ignore Allow and Disallow Options for java.security.manager System Property ([JDK-8301118](
In JDK 12, two new token options for the java.security.manager system property, "allow" and "disallow", were introduced.
Many applications and frameworks are designed to run on multiple JDKs. For those that enable the SecurityManager at runtime via System.setSecurityManager, they have to specify the "allow" option as of JDK 18 (see [JDK-8203316]( However, these applications would also prefer to use the same command line across multiple versions of the JDK, especially if it is not known what JDK version a user will use.
Currently, if these options are specified in JDK 12 or earlier, the runtime attempts to load a SecurityManager implementation with the classname "allow" or "disallow", which results in a Could not create SecurityManager Error and the application will not start up.
From this release onward, the "allow" and "disallow" options for the java.security.manager system property will be ignored.

issue_title: jdk22 -Xdebug and -debug options deprecated for removal and should print deprecation warning
description:
Copied from the jdk22 release notes.
-Xdebug and -debug Options Are Deprecated for Removal ([JDK-8227229](
tools/launcher
The -Xdebug and -debug options of the java command have been deprecated for removal. These options have been ignored for several releases and don't provide any functionality. Using either of these options while launching java will now log a deprecation warning.
Existing applications which use either of these options should be updated to remove references to these options.
-Xnoagent Option Is Deprecated for Removal ([JDK-8312072](
hotspot/runtime
The -Xnoagent option of the java command has been deprecated for removal. This option has been ignored for many releases and doesn't provide any functionality. It will now generate a deprecation warning when used while launching java.
Any existing code which uses this option should be updated to remove reference to this option.

issue_title: Fix JVMTI_HEAP_REFERENCE_JNI_LOCAL scan/iterate code
description:
Based on discussion from `wrapObjectIterationCallback` called in `jvmtiIterateOverReachableObjects` uses `event->type` to differentiate reference kind and which callback to use which uses `(J9WalkState *) referrer` casting for stack type.
Previously GC would report JNI local refs in the first 16 slots as STACK_LOCAL (stored on the NativeCallout frame) and any after that as JNI_LOCAL (frame stored in the jniLocalReferences list). The JVMTI code is required to correct JNI refs reported as STACK_LOCAL before calling user stack ref callback while JNI_LOCAL would be incorrectly sent to user's heap root callback.
With the code change from #18378 and #18379, all JNI locals should be correctly reported, but since they still map to J9JVMTI_HEAP_EVENT_ROOT, this cause call jni refs to be sent to user's heap root callback which doesn't match the JVMTI spec Changes required:
1. map `J9GC_ROOT_TYPE_JNI_LOCAL` to `J9JVMTI_HEAP_EVENT_STACK`
2. refactor `wrapObjectIterationCallback` to correctly handle jni refs that doesn't come from stack walking
3. fix `processStackRoot` code to first recognize references kind rather than relying on walkState.
4. fix function parameter type(
I will create a draft PR on the above changes as a starting point for further discussion.
FYI @LinHu2016 @amicic @babsingh @keithc-ca
creator: fengxue-IS

The JVMTI code is required to correct JNI refs reported as STACK_LOCAL before calling user stack ref callback while JNI_LOCAL would be incorrectly sent to user's heap root callback.
With the code change from #18378 and #18379, all JNI locals should be correctly reported, but since they still map to J9JVMTI_HEAP_EVENT_ROOT, this cause call jni refs to be sent to user's heap root callback which doesn't match the JVMTI spec Changes required:
1. map `J9GC_ROOT_TYPE_JNI_LOCAL` to `J9JVMTI_HEAP_EVENT_STACK`
2. refactor `wrapObjectIterationCallback` to correctly handle jni refs that doesn't come from stack walking
3. fix `processStackRoot` code to first recognize references kind rather than relying on walkState.
4. fix function parameter type(

issue_title: Disable CRIUSecProvider when specific option is set during checkpoint
description:
Whenever performing a checkpoint using openj9 we are typically able to do something like the following:
java -XX:+EnableCRIUSupport QuickTest
When called by default all security providers are removed from the runtime environment and the `CRIUSecProvider` is inserted into the runtime. This approach provides a safer approach to locking down what cryptography is allowed during the checkpoint phase and additionally forces MessageDigests supported to be reset and SHA1PRNG instances to reset their seeds that are in use.
We would like to introduce a new option named `-XX:+EnableFullSecurityEnv`. Using this option all checkpoint related security considerations shift from the responsibility of a Java runtime to the application owner and deployment model in use:
java -XX:+EnableCRIUSupport -XX:+EnableFullSecurityEnv QuickTest
With this option we no longer make use of the `CRIUSecProvider` in any fashion. In this case we would use the default set of providers and algorithms to enable full functionality prior to checkpoint.
There have been a few use cases identified so far for this option. Both of these cases assume that the application designers are able to correctly handle some CRIU specific concerns such as forcing the use of entropy sources correctly for random numbers in use, zeroing memory, de-referencing sensitive objects, protected CRIU files at an OS level using correct permissions, and other security related tasks assigned with general protection of a file at rest. The main uses cases are as follows:
- Users are not making use of "real" sensitive fields prior to checkpoint. In this case they no longer need any additional processing in the CRIU provider, nor restrictions on algorithms, since they are not making use of real sensitive information prior to checkpoint. This use case is a real world use case in place for spring boot applications running within liberty. - Deployments may choose to make use of disk encryption or any other encryption technologies to secure checkpoint files at rest. In this case all values are encrypted and cannot be exposed by design to others.
Both of these use cases can also be combined.
This option also provides the following additional advantages over the use of the CRIUSecProvider strategy outlined above:
- Resetting the state of algorithms, setting seeds of random generators, and clearing sensitive values may or may not be a desired behavior for the users applications.
- The CRIUSecProvider has very limited functionality that is currently supported. Over time this will require more and more additional algorithms to be developed and deployed on a case by case basis for a given CRIU use case.
- Other solutions that are are available today from other runtimes support this type of hands off approach.
We propose to implement this option as a non default option due to the risks of using such an approach.

issue_title: Remove java.lang.Compiler from Java 21+
description:
It was removed upstream via Also the following
core-libs/java.lang
[➜]( Removal of the java.compiler System Property ([JDK-8041676](
The system property java.compiler has been removed from the list of standard system properties.
Running with this system property set on the command line will now print a warning to say that the system property is obsolete; it has no other effect. In previous releases, running with -Djava.compiler or -Djava.compiler=NONE on the command line selected interpreter only execution mode. If needed, the -Xint option can be used to run in interpreter only mode.
creator: keithc-ca
text:
Bug Title: Remove java.lang.Compiler from Java 21+
Bug Description: It was removed upstream via Also the following
core-libs/java.lang
[➜]( Removal of the java.compiler System Property ([JDK-8041676](
The system property java.compiler has been removed from the list of standard system properties.
Running with this system property set on the command line will now print a warning to say that the system property is obsolete; it has no other effect. In previous releases, running with -Djava.compiler or -Djava.compiler=NONE on the command line selected interpreter only execution mode. If needed, the -Xint option can be used to run in interpreter only mode.

issue_title: Avoid unsteady states during JVMTI Suspend and Resume All VThreads
description:
For VThreads, the `mount` and `unmount` phases are unsteady states since a `J9VMThread` is modified during these phases.
JVMTI `[Suspend|Resume]AllVirtualThreads` acquire exclusive VM access. This can pause the virtual threads or carrier threads in the middle of the `mount` and `unmount` phases. Effects of the above issue:
- Suspended threads might still run;
- Resuming threads might encounter threads that are not suspended; and
- JVMTI events might trigger for the suspended threads.
The above issue hasn't been reproduced due to the small gap in the `mount` and `unmount` phases.
creator: babsingh
text:
Bug Title: Avoid unsteady states during JVMTI Suspend and Resume All VThreads
Bug Description: For VThreads, the `mount` and `unmount` phases are unsteady states since a `J9VMThread` is modified during these phases.
JVMTI `[Suspend|Resume]AllVirtualThreads` acquire exclusive VM access. This can pause the virtual threads or carrier threads in the middle of the `mount` and `unmount` phases. Effects of the above issue:
- Suspended threads might still run;
- Resuming threads might encounter threads that are not suspended; and
- JVMTI events might trigger for the suspended threads.
The above issue hasn't been reproduced due to the small gap in the `mount` and `unmount` phases.

issue_title: Valhalla disables JDK22+ Jep454Tests temporarily
description:
Current [valhalla]( is at `jdk-22+15` which is well behind OpenJDK head [jdk-23+1](
This gap caused the merging conflicts for [openj9-openjdk-jdk.valuetypes]( preventing merging with recent OpenJDK updates, and causing valhalla PR test failures:
 [javac] /home/jenkins/workspace/Test_openjdknext_j9_sanity.functional_x86-64_linux_vt_standard_Personal_testList_1/aqa-tests/functional/Java22andUp/src/org/openj9/test/jep454/upcall/InvalidUpCallTests.java:308: error: method critical in interface Option cannot be applied to given types;
 [javac] MethodHandle mh = linker.downcallHandle(functionSymbol, fd, Linker.Option.critical(false));
 [javac] ^
 [javac] required: no arguments
 [javac] found: boolean
 [javac] reason: actual and formal argument lists differ in length
 [javac] 4 errors
 BUILD FAILED
Resolving the merging conflict and porting OpenJDK `jdk-23+1` changes to Valhalla extension repo requires large changes and seems risky.
Proposing [Valhalla disables JDK22+ Jep454Tests temporarily]( until the Valhalla project is updated with a recent OpenJDK tag.
creator: JasonFengJ9

issue_title: [Loom] Implement JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend
description:
A stub was added for `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` (JDK23 only) in As per `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` will eventually be ported to JDK22.
Also, the assertion in the stub will be triggered because `notifyJvmtiDisableSuspend -> JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` is used in `VirtualThread` methods such as `unpark`, `interrupt`, `getAndClearInterrupt`, `threadState`, and `toString`: To avoid triggering the assertion, the stub needs to be empty.
As for the implementation, this method notifies JVMTI to disable `JVMTI suspend` operations for a `VirtualThread` by toggling a field on/off. The intent is to ignore `JVMTI suspend` operations when a `VirtualThread` is performing certain synchronized blocks related to its carrier thread.
 Next steps
- Verify if the bug exists in OpenJ9 using the test case (`Repro8311218.java`) from - If it doesn't exist, then let `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` stay emtpy.
- If the bug exists in OpenJ9, then implement `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` using the above description after verifying if the JVMTI operations are `skipped` or `delayed (wait)` until the `VirtualThread` completes the synchronized block.
creator: babsingh
text:
Bug Title: [Loom] Implement JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend
Bug Description: A stub was added for `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` (JDK23 only) in As per `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` will eventually be ported to JDK22.
Also, the assertion in the stub will be triggered because `notifyJvmtiDisableSuspend -> JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` is used in `VirtualThread` methods such as `unpark`, `interrupt`, `getAndClearInterrupt`, `threadState`, and `toString`: To avoid triggering the assertion, the stub needs to be empty.
As for the implementation, this method notifies JVMTI to disable `JVMTI suspend` operations for a `VirtualThread` by toggling a field on/off. The intent is to ignore `JVMTI suspend` operations when a `VirtualThread` is performing certain synchronized blocks related to its carrier thread.
 Next steps
- Verify if the bug exists in OpenJ9 using the test case (`Repro8311218.java`) from - If it doesn't exist, then let `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` stay emtpy.
- If the bug exists in OpenJ9, then implement `JVM_VirtualThreadDisableSuspend` using the above description after verifying if the JVMTI operations are `skipped` or `delayed (wait)` until the `VirtualThread` completes the synchronized block.

description:

FAILED: test_verifyJVMTIMacros

The VirtualThread states in jdk22 are different from jdk21 and the test.
 private static final int NEW = 0;
 private static final int STARTED = 1;

 private static final int PARKED = 4; // unmounted
 private static final int PINNED = 5; // mounted
 private static final int TIMED_PARKING = 6;
 private static final int TIMED_PARKED = 7; // unmounted
 private static final int TIMED_PINNED = 8; // mounted
 private static final int UNPARKED = 9; // unmounted but runnable

issue_title: Attach mechanism implementation needs to prevent deletion of notification files by systemd
description:
By default, the JVM's Attach mechanism places its notification files in the system temporary directory, typically in a sub-directory in `/tmp/.com_ibm_tools_attach`. My understanding is that the JVM does not open, modify or read from these files after they have been created.
This causes a problem for long running JVM processes in Linux environments that use `systemd`, because by default `systemd-tmpfiles` will automatically delete files in `/tmp` that haven't been accessed for 10 days. More information can be found here:
Obviously the user can specify a different location in which to place the Attach notification files using the `com.ibm.tools.attach.directory` system property, but out of the box the Attach mechanism will fail for JVMs that run for longer than 10 days.
There are various options outlined in the paged linked above for protecting temp files from automatic deletion. I think the JVM should implement one of these options.
creator: paulcheeseman
text:
Bug Title: Attach mechanism implementation needs to prevent deletion of notification files by systemd
Bug Description: By default, the JVM's Attach mechanism places its notification files in the system temporary directory, typically in a sub-directory in `/tmp/.com_ibm_tools_attach`. My understanding is that the JVM does not open, modify or read from these files after they have been created.
This causes a problem for long running JVM processes in Linux environments that use `systemd`, because by default `systemd-tmpfiles` will automatically delete files in `/tmp` that haven't been accessed for 10 days. More information can be found here:
Obviously the user can specify a different location in which to place the Attach notification files using the `com.ibm.tools.attach.directory` system property, but out of the box the Attach mechanism will fail for JVMs that run for longer than 10 days.
There are various options outlined in the paged linked above for protecting temp files from automatic deletion. I think the JVM should implement one of these options.

issue_title: Reflection problem with umlaut character, seemingly related to String compression
description:
Consider the following test program:
public class Test {
 public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
 String umlautA = "ä";
 String methodName = "get" + umlautA;
 Test.class.getDeclaredMethod(methodName);
 }
 public static String getä() {
 return "ä";
 }
}
If this is compiled with any IBM Java 8 or Semeru 8 release, and then executed on Semeru 11.0.21.0, it will fail with a NoSuchMethodException when trying to find the getä() method:
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoSuchMethodException: Test.getä()
 at java.base/java.lang.Class.newNoSuchMethodException(Class.java:649)
 at java.base/java.lang.Class.throwExceptionOrReturnNull(Class.java:1447)
 at java.base/java.lang.Class.getMethodHelper(Class.java:1533)
 at java.base/java.lang.Class.getDeclaredMethod(Class.java:1121)
 at Test.main(Test.java:5)
Some observations from my own experiments:
- If the program is run on Semeru 11.0.20.0 the failure does not occur
- If the program is run on the latest IBM Java 8 and Semeru 8 releases the failure does not occur
- If the program is compiled with any Semeru 11 release the failure does not occur
- String compression [was enabled by default]( in Semeru 11.0.21.0, and if the program is run on 11.0.21.0 with the option `-XX:-CompactStrings` to disable String compression the failure does not occur
- The way that the `methodName` String is constructed is significant - if the test program is changed to use any of the following alternatives the failure **does not** occur:
 - `String methodName = "getä";`
 - `String methodName = "get" + "ä";`
 - `String methodName = "" + "getä";`
- The bytecode for the String concatenation that's created with Java/Semeru 8's `javac` is quite different to Semeru 11's, which is probably significant:
**Java/Semeru 8:**
 public static void main(java.lang.String[]) throws java.lang.Exception;
 Code:
 0: ldc #2 // String ä
 2: astore_1
 3: new #3 // class java/lang/StringBuilder
 6: dup
 7: invokespecial #4 // Method java/lang/StringBuilder."<init>":()V
 10: ldc #5 // String get
 12: invokevirtual #6 // Method java/lang/StringBuilder.append:(Ljava/lang/String;)Ljava/lang/StringBuilder;
 15: aload_1
 16: invokevirtual #6 // Method java/lang/StringBuilder.append:(Ljava/lang/String;)Ljava/lang/StringBuilder;
 19: invokevirtual #7 // Method java/lang/StringBuilder.toString:()Ljava/lang/String;
 22: astore_2
 23: ldc #8 // class Test
 25: aload_2
 26: iconst_0
 27: anewarray #9 // class java/lang/Class
 30: invokevirtual #10 // Method java/lang/Class.getDeclaredMethod:(Ljava/lang/String;[Ljava/lang/Class;)Ljava/lang/reflect/Method;
 33: pop
 34: return
**Semeru 11:**
 public static void main(java.lang.String[]) throws java.lang.Exception;
 Code:
 0: ldc #2 // String ä
 2: astore_1
 3: aload_1
 4: invokedynamic #3, 0 // InvokeDynamic #0:makeConcatWithConstants:(Ljava/lang/String;)Ljava/lang/String;
 9: astore_2
 10: ldc #4 // class Test
 12: aload_2
 13: iconst_0
 14: anewarray #5 // class java/lang/Class
 17: invokevirtual #6 // Method java/lang/Class.getDeclaredMethod:(Ljava/lang/String;[Ljava/lang/Class;)Ljava/lang/reflect/Method;
 20: pop
 21: return
Internal 150545
creator: paulcheeseman

issue_title: New field access flag in Valhalla
description:
In the latest Valhalla draft spec
`ACC_STRICT(<hex>)` is added to the field access flags in value type, indicating
`A strictly-enforced final field; may only be assigned at the start of object construction.`
The following change in [section 4.5]( requires OpenJ9 to update the class format check: A field must not have set both ACC_FINAL and ACC_VOLATILE, and must not have set both ACC_STRICT and ACC_STATIC.
A field that has set ACC_STRICT must also have set ACC_FINAL.
Each field of a value class must have exactly one of its ACC_STATIC or ACC_STRICT flags set.
The additional check of `ACC_STRICT` in [4.10.1.9]( requires OpenJ9 to update the verification code.
creator: hangshao0
text:
Bug Title: New field access flag in Valhalla
Bug Description: In the latest Valhalla draft spec
`ACC_STRICT(<hex>)` is added to the field access flags in value type, indicating
`A strictly-enforced final field; may only be assigned at the start of object construction.`
The following change in [section 4.5]( requires OpenJ9 to update the class format check: A field must not have set both ACC_FINAL and ACC_VOLATILE, and must not have set both ACC_STRICT and ACC_STATIC.
A field that has set ACC_STRICT must also have set ACC_FINAL.
Each field of a value class must have exactly one of its ACC_STATIC or ACC_STRICT flags set.
The additional check of `ACC_STRICT` in [4.10.1.9]( requires OpenJ9 to update the verification code.

issue_title: Semeru 8 throws an InternalError with option -Djava.security.manager=allow instead of ignoring it
description:
According to the documentation for OpenJ9 0.41 (used in Semeru 8.0.392.0) the option `-Djava.security.manager=allow` should be ignored from this release onwards:
> From OpenJDK version 18 onwards, if you enable the SecurityManager at runtime by calling the System.setSecurityManager() API, you must set the -Djava.security.manager=allow option. To disable the SecurityManager, you must specify the -Djava.security.manager=disallow option. If an application is designed to run on multiple OpenJDK versions, the same command line might be used across multiple versions. Because of this use of the same command line across multiple versions, in OpenJDK versions before version 18, the runtime attempts to load a SecurityManager with the class name allow or disallow resulted in an error and the application was not starting.
> > To resolve this issue, OpenJDK version 17 ignores these options. **With this release, OpenJDK versions 8 and 11 also ignore the allow and disallow keywords, if specified**.
However, Semeru 8.0.392.0 (which uses OpenJ9 0.41) and later Semeru 8 releases fail to launch with an InternalError when the option `-Djava.security.manager=allow` (or `-Djava.security.manager=disallow`) is specified. For example, with 8.0.402.0:
> java -Djava.security.manager=allow -version
Exception in thread "main" java/lang/InternalError: Could not create SecurityManager: allow
 at sun/misc/Launcher.<init> (Launcher.java:106)
 at sun/misc/Launcher.<clinit> (Launcher.java:54)
 at java/lang/ClassLoader.initializeClassLoaders (ClassLoader.java:196)
 at java/lang/Thread.initialize (Thread.java:404)
 at java/lang/Thread.<init> (Thread.java:161)
I checked with the latest Semeru 8 nightly and it still has the same issue. The equivalent Semeru 11 release (11.0.21.0) and later Semeru 11 releases ignore the option as expected.
The problem appears to involve [this line of code]( Maybe there should be a call to [System.initSecurityManager()]( here instead?
creator: paulcheeseman

issue_title: Change to ValueType comparison
description:
The value type comparison regarding float and double has been changed [here:](
For fields of type float, the values are the same if, after applying the conversion defined by the method Float.floatToRawIntBits, a comparison via if_icmpeq would succeed.
For fields of type double, the values are the same if, after applying the conversion defined by the method Double.doubleToRawLongBits, a comparison via lcmp would produce 0.
`Float.floatToRawIntBits` and `Double.doubleToRawLongBits` are changed from `Float.floatToIntBits` and `Double.doubleToLongBits`. In the new spec, it won't collapse all the bit patterns of NaN anymore in VT comparison. The flag `J9ClassCanSupportFastSubstitutability` can now be set for VT with float/double fields, which allows for direct memory comparison. `VM_ValueTypeHelpers::isSubstitutable()` needs to be updated on float and double comparison as well.
creator: hangshao0
text:
Bug Title: Change to ValueType comparison
Bug Description: The value type comparison regarding float and double has been changed [here:](
For fields of type float, the values are the same if, after applying the conversion defined by the method Float.floatToRawIntBits, a comparison via if_icmpeq would succeed.
For fields of type double, the values are the same if, after applying the conversion defined by the method Double.doubleToRawLongBits, a comparison via lcmp would produce 0.
`Float.floatToRawIntBits` and `Double.doubleToRawLongBits` are changed from `Float.floatToIntBits` and `Double.doubleToLongBits`. In the new spec, it won't collapse all the bit patterns of NaN anymore in VT comparison. The flag `J9ClassCanSupportFastSubstitutability` can now be set for VT with float/double fields, which allows for direct memory comparison. `VM_ValueTypeHelpers::isSubstitutable()` needs to be updated on float and double comparison as well.

issue_title: Remove _magic_ constant `J9_FFI_DOWNCALL_HEAP_ARGUMENT_ID`
description: `J9_FFI_DOWNCALL_HEAP_ARGUMENT_ID` was originally `<hex>`, but changed to `<hex>` in #19002. No matter what value is chosen, it's possible it conflicts with application intent. As I [suggested]( I think we should use an out-of-band channel to distinguish parameters that should point within the heap from other parameters.
creator: keithc-ca
text:
Bug Title: Remove _magic_ constant `J9_FFI_DOWNCALL_HEAP_ARGUMENT_ID`
Bug Description: `J9_FFI_DOWNCALL_HEAP_ARGUMENT_ID` was originally `<hex>`, but changed to `<hex>` in #19002. No matter what value is chosen, it's possible it conflicts with application intent. As I [suggested]( I think we should use an out-of-band channel to distinguish parameters that should point within the heap from other parameters.

issue_title: Investigate VirtualThread wait(), wait(timeout), sleep() behaviour
description:
In JDK22, a new test, [GetThreadStateMountedTest]( was added to verify the behaviour of interrupting a virtual thread while it is suspended using JVMTI.
The behaviour between a thread suspended by JVMTI and it receiving an interrupt is not properly defined in the Java doc and JVMTI spec. The goal of this issue is to verify the below [Thread.interrupt]( behaviour for a thread suspended by JVMTI:
> If this thread is blocked in an invocation of the [wait()]( [wait(long)]( or [wait(long, int)]( methods of the [Object]( class, or of the [join()]( [join(long)]( [join(long, int)]( [sleep(long)]( or [sleep(long, int)]( methods of this class, then its interrupt status will be cleared and it will receive an [InterruptedException](
If a thread is suspended while executing `wait()/wait(timeout)/sleep()` and it receives an interrupt, should the thread throw an `InterruptedException` after resuming?
After running [GetThreadStateMountedTest]( using the JDK22 RI, it was found that the RI never throws an `InterruptedException` for `waiting(timeout)` and `sleeping`. It intermittently throws an `InterruptedException` for `waiting` indefinitely (without a `timeout`), but most of the time it didn't throw an `InterruptedException` even for this case. The test is missing asserts to validate `InterruptedException` because the RI doesn't guarantee to throw an `InterruptedException`.
Based upon the above RI behaviour, throwing an `InterruptedException` is neither expected nor guaranteed.
creator: babsingh
text:
Bug Title: Investigate VirtualThread wait(), wait(timeout), sleep() behaviour
Bug Description: In JDK22, a new test, [GetThreadStateMountedTest]( was added to verify the behaviour of interrupting a virtual thread while it is suspended using JVMTI.
The behaviour between a thread suspended by JVMTI and it receiving an interrupt is not properly defined in the Java doc and JVMTI spec. The goal of this issue is to verify the below [Thread.interrupt]( behaviour for a thread suspended by JVMTI:
> If this thread is blocked in an invocation of the [wait()]( [wait(long)]( or [wait(long, int)]( methods of the [Object]( class, or of the [join()]( [join(long)]( [join(long, int)]( [sleep(long)]( or [sleep(long, int)]( methods of this class, then its interrupt status will be cleared and it will receive an [InterruptedException](
If a thread is suspended while executing `wait()/wait(timeout)/sleep()` and it receives an interrupt, should the thread throw an `InterruptedException` after resuming?
After running [GetThreadStateMountedTest]( using the JDK22 RI, it was found that the RI never throws an `InterruptedException` for `waiting(timeout)` and `sleeping`. It intermittently throws an `InterruptedException` for `waiting` indefinitely (without a `timeout`), but most of the time it didn't throw an `InterruptedException` even for this case. The test is missing asserts to validate `InterruptedException` because the RI doesn't guarantee to throw an `InterruptedException`.
Based upon the above RI behaviour, throwing an `InterruptedException` is neither expected nor guaranteed.

issue_title: JCMD support for selecting JVM by applications
description:
Currently in openj9 when sending a command to JVM one needs to run `jcmd -l` which outputs the pid's for all the JVMs found on the machine. After one needs to do `jcmd [pid] [command]` to send the command. Which means that two steps are required.
With openJDK one does not need to know the [pid], one can simply use the application name as the ID to send the command to (ie. `jcmd [appName] [command]`. This means that only a single step is required.
Example:
Sending checkpoint command with J9:
jcmd -l
//list JVMs
433707 ./target/spring-boot-crac-demo-1.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar
433759 <no information available>
//trigger checkpoint
jcmd 433707 JDK.checkpoint
JVM checkpoint requested
On OpenJDK
//one step
jcmd ./target/spring-boot-crac-demo-1.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar JDK.checkpoint
JVM checkpoint requested
creator: tajila

issue_title: Refactor javacore output for virtual threads
description:
Currently in javacore, the following thread info is included:
0SECTION THREADS subcomponent dump routine
NULL NULL
1XMPOOLINFO JVM Thread pool info:
2XMPOOLTOTAL Current total number of pooled threads: 63
2XMPOOLLIVE Current total number of live threads: 59
2XMPOOLDAEMON Current total number of live daemon threads: 57
NULL
1XMTHDINFO Thread Details
NULL
3XMTHREADINFO "main" J9VMThread:<hex>, omrthread_t:<hex>, java/lang/Thread:<hex>, state:CW, prio=5
3XMJAVALTHREAD (java/lang/Thread getId:<hex>, isDaemon:false)
...
the option `-XX:+ShowUnmountedThreadStacks` added a new section for unmounted virtual/carrier thread data which is not included in the `Thread Details` section.
1XMVTHDINFO Unmounted Threads
NULL NULL
3XMVTHDINFO "ForkJoinPool-1-worker-1" [mounted] J9VMContinuation:<hex>, java/lang/Thread:<hex>
3XMVTHDINFO1 Type: Carrier, J9VMThread:<hex>, java/lang/VirtualThread:<hex>
3XMTHREADINFO3 Java callstack:
However, it is still missing the following data which would be useful for profiling/monitoring/debugging
Current total number of carrier threads
Current total number of virtual threads
Current total number of started virtual threads
Current total number of finished virtual threads (maybe)
in addition, there could be an option to specify virtual threads that have not been first mounted should be included in the `Unmounted Threads` section (currently only threads with a valid stack is included)
FYI @tajila @babsingh for inputs

issue_title: Ignore exceptions when speculatively loading class in Preload attribute
description:
From the [spec](
If C has a Preload attribute, a Java Virtual Machine implementation may optionally use L to speculatively load any of the classes or interfaces mentioned by symbolic references listed in the classes array of the Preload attribute.
When speculatively loading a class or interface, any exception that is thrown as a result of failure to load the class or interface is ignored and discarded. This step of derivation always completes successfully.
creator: hangshao0

When speculatively loading a class or interface, any exception that is thrown as a result of failure to load the class or interface is ignored and discarded. This step of derivation always completes successfully.

issue_title: Placeholder for code temporarily disabled for Valhalla
description:
This is a placeholder for OpenJ9 changes required but not supported by Valhalla project yet due to [openj9-openjdk-jdk.valuetypes]( lags behind the head-stream.
The code in question will be decorated with `!INLINE-TYPES ` which should be removed when the [openj9-openjdk-jdk.valuetypes]( consumes the corresponding openjdk contents.
FYI @hangshao0
creator: JasonFengJ9
text:

issue_title: Unload stale package entries from classHashTable
description:
When anonymous classes were first introduced in Java 8 their packages were always inherited from a parent class that is loaded first. Since the parent class would only get unloaded when the class loader does the package entry in classHashTable, which rely's on a valid romClass, was always valid.
It is possible in some situations such as MethodHandle Proxies that package names are not inherited from a parent but generated specially for the hidden class. If the rom class gets unloaded, that package entry in the classHashTable will crash when accessed such as was seen in The MethodHandle Proxy case was solved: I'm creating this issue as a reminder to investigate further when else this can occur and create a more general solution to solve this problem.
creator: theresa-m
text:
Bug Title: Unload stale package entries from classHashTable
Bug Description: When anonymous classes were first introduced in Java 8 their packages were always inherited from a parent class that is loaded first. Since the parent class would only get unloaded when the class loader does the package entry in classHashTable, which rely's on a valid romClass, was always valid.
It is possible in some situations such as MethodHandle Proxies that package names are not inherited from a parent but generated specially for the hidden class. If the rom class gets unloaded, that package entry in the classHashTable will crash when accessed such as was seen in The MethodHandle Proxy case was solved: I'm creating this issue as a reminder to investigate further when else this can occur and create a more general solution to solve this problem.

issue_title: Collect jpackcore console output in the zip file
description: jpackcore prints information to the console which may be useful for diagnostics if something goes wrong. Rather than having to ask the user for the jpackcore console output, we could collect it and include it as a file in the zip.
creator: pshipton
text:
Bug Title: Collect jpackcore console output in the zip file
Bug Description: jpackcore prints information to the console which may be useful for diagnostics if something goes wrong. Rather than having to ask the user for the jpackcore console output, we could collect it and include it as a file in the zip.

issue_title: Build-test pipeline doesn't support custom aqa-test repo
description:
Launching a build via the jenkins pipeline doesn't allow passing in a custom aqa-test repo/branch. This makes testing against excluded test needing a lot of extra work in order to ensure test coverage without generating regressions.
FYI @llxia
creator: fengxue-IS
text:
Bug Title: Build-test pipeline doesn't support custom aqa-test repo
Bug Description: Launching a build via the jenkins pipeline doesn't allow passing in a custom aqa-test repo/branch. This makes testing against excluded test needing a lot of extra work in order to ensure test coverage without generating regressions.
FYI @llxia

issue_title: Recent JDK11 ojdk292 builds on Jenkins fail with unrecognized configuration option
description:
The `ojdk292` platform suffix in Jenkins is used to enable OpenJDK MethodHandles for Java 8 and Java 11.
Recent JDK11 `ojdk292` builds on Jenkins fail with the following:
configure: error: unrecognized options: --enable-openjdk-methodhandles
Everything is fine for JDK8 `ojdk292` builds.
Here is an example:
creator: ThanHenderson
text:
Bug Title: Recent JDK11 ojdk292 builds on Jenkins fail with unrecognized configuration option
Bug Description: The `ojdk292` platform suffix in Jenkins is used to enable OpenJDK MethodHandles for Java 8 and Java 11.
Recent JDK11 `ojdk292` builds on Jenkins fail with the following:
configure: error: unrecognized options: --enable-openjdk-methodhandles
Everything is fine for JDK8 `ojdk292` builds.
Here is an example:

issue_title: Using full command line as GC hints key causes key proliferation
description: The Java command line may have unique elements which are irrelevant to GC hints, causing multiple keys to be created when the GC hints are going to be the same. Using the entire command line can also make the keys very long and complex, which increases the work to search for a matching key when a new JVM instance is launched. This extra unnecessary work slows down JVM startup.
creator: gjdeval
text:
Bug Title: Using full command line as GC hints key causes key proliferation
Bug Description: The Java command line may have unique elements which are irrelevant to GC hints, causing multiple keys to be created when the GC hints are going to be the same. Using the entire command line can also make the keys very long and complex, which increases the work to search for a matching key when a new JVM instance is launched. This extra unnecessary work slows down JVM startup.

description:

Eclipse OpenJ9 VM 21.0.2.0 (build openj9-0.43.0, JRE 21 Windows 11 amd64-64-Bit Compressed References 20240116_95 (JIT enabled, AOT enabled)
OpenJ9 - 2c3d78b48
OMR - ea8124dbc
JCL - 78c4500a434 based on jdk-21.0.2+13)
Summary of problem
The inability to run jcmd and late attach is observed both with WebSphere traditional and WebSphere Liberty which use different mechanisms to create Windows Services, so I'm guessing it's not related to those mechanisms directly (note: Liberty uses [Apache commons daemon]( prunsrv.exe). The command prompt running jcmd is started as Administrator. In the example below, the Liberty-generated Windows Service launches Liberty under javaw.exe but the WAS traditional-generated Windows Service launches WebSphere traditional under java.exe.
Steps to reproduce:
1. Download <
1. Extract
1. Open command prompt as Administrator
1. Add Semeru to PATH; for example:
 set PATH=C:\work\semeru\21.0.2.0\jdk-21.0.2+13\bin;%PATH%
 1. Change directory to the extracted directory of Liberty
1. Create the test Liberty server:
 wlp\bin\server create server1
 1. Append a line to `wlp\usr\servers\server1\server.env` to specify Semeru in the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable; for example:
 JAVA_HOME=C:\work\semeru\21.0.2.0\jdk-21.0.2+13
 1. Create the Windows Service for the Liberty server:
 wlp\bin\server registerWinService server1
 1. Start the Windows Service:
 wlp\bin\server startWinService server1
 1. Find the process ID of the javaw.exe for the Liberty server underneath the Windows Service:
 wmic process where 'commandline like "%server1%"' get caption,processid | findstr javaw
 For example:
 javaw.exe 4584
 1. Run jmcd with the list option and observe the PID from the previous command is not listed (I think what's listed is jcmd itself); for example:
 jcmd -l
 26248 <no information available>
 The issue is also observed with late attach:
1. Download [IBM Runtime Diagnostic Code Injection for the Java Platform (Java Surgery)](
